1         Overview

This document contains descriptions and XML examples for a variety of the indicative data scenarios.

These examples should be reviewed in conjunction with the Indicative Data specification (see Appendix B – Related Documents).

2         Trading Partner Roles

The Indicative Data schemas support the exchange of enrollment and payroll information between trading partners.  Trading partners may be large employers, HR software vendors, third party administrators, or insurance carriers.

The role of the trading partner within the context of the Indicative Data schemas is to communicate and/or receive benefit enrollment information as it relates to a subscriber or dependent. 


3         Reference Examples

3.1        Example A – William’s Story

William Jones started working at the Canadian Widget Manufacturing company. He moved his family to New York, when his job was transferred to the US branch. William took a leave of absence when his son was born. He voluntarily left Acme and was re-hired within a year. Shortly afterward, the company was acquired by Acme.

 

Example A1— New Hire

January 1, 1987 - William Jones started working at Widget Manufacturing.

 

Example A2 – Address Change

June 06, 1998 – William transferred to US branch of company. Changed family address to New York.

 

Example A3 – Leave of Absence

March 21, 1999 – William went on FMLA (family leave) but decided to use his 6 weeks of vacation so that his leave would be paid. He intended to return work on May 4.  

 

May 1, 1999 – William informed his boss that he needed to extend his leave since they were unable to find a nanny. He expected to return to work on June 20.  His leave switched from paid to unpaid as his vacation was exhausted.

 

June 20, 1999 – William returned to work.

 

Example A4 – Termination

October 18, 2003 – William voluntarily terminated employment with Widget.

 

Example A5 – Rehire

June 21, 2004 – William was re-hired at Widget.

 

Example A6 – Acquisition (Snapshot)

October 25, 2004 - Acme (Manufacturing Division) acquired Widget Manufacturing.

 

Example A7 – Acquisition (History)

January 1, 1987 - William Jones started working at Widget Manufacturing. 

August 28, 1996 - William married Margaret and added her as a dependent.

June 06, 1998 – William transferred to US branch of company. Changed family address to New York.

March 21, 1999 – William and Margaret had a son, Paul, and added him as a dependent.

March 21 – June 20, 1999 – William took a 3 month leave of absence.

October 18, 2003 – William voluntarily terminated employment with Widget.

June 21, 2004 – William was re-hired at Widget.

October 25, 2004 - Acme (Manufacturing Division) acquired Widget Manufacturing.

3.1.1          Example A1 – New Hire

January 1, 1987 - William Jones started working at Widget Manufacturing. This document represents the indicative information that may be used by a benefits outsourcer or payroll vendor.

 

 <IndicativeBatch>

      <TransactionType>Full</TransactionType>

      <CreateDate>1987-01-31</CreateDate>

      <BaselineDate>1987-01-31</BaselineDate>

      <IndicativeData>

             <Employer>

                   <OrganizationName>Widget Manufacturing</OrganizationName>

                   <OrganizationId idOwner="Dunn &amp; Bradstreet">

                         <IdValue name="DUNNS">72241</IdValue>

                   </OrganizationId>

             </Employer>

             <Employee>

                   <PersonInfo>

                         <PersonLegalId validFrom="1961-04-05" validTo="2000-05-11" idOwner="Canadian Social Insurance">

                                <IdValue name="SIN">123-456-789</IdValue>

                         </PersonLegalId>

                         <PersonName>

                                <GivenName>William</GivenName>

                                <FamilyName>Jones</FamilyName>

                         </PersonName>

                         <DateOfBirth>1961-04-05</DateOfBirth>

                         <GenderCode>1</GenderCode>

                         <MaritalStatus>

                                <StandardValue>Unmarried</StandardValue>

                         </MaritalStatus>

                         <ContactInfo validFrom="1987-01-01">

                                <Location>home</Location>

                                <WhenAvailable>evenings</WhenAvailable>

                                <Telephone>

                                      <FormattedNumber>(418)555-9876</FormattedNumber>

                                </Telephone>

                                <PostalAddress>

                                      <CountryCode>CA</CountryCode>

                                      <PostalCode>G1R 5C7</PostalCode>

                                      <Region>Quebec</Region>

                                      <Municipality>Quebec City</Municipality>

                                      <DeliveryAddress>

                                            <AddressLine>875, rue Fraser</AddressLine>

                                      </DeliveryAddress>

                                </PostalAddress>

                         </ContactInfo>

                   </PersonInfo>

                   <EmployeeInfo>

                         <EmployeeId validFrom="1987-01-01" idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                                <IdValue name="EE Id">320</IdValue>

                         </EmployeeId>

                         <ContactInfo validFrom="1987-01-01">

                                <Location>office</Location>

                                <WhenAvailable>weekdays</WhenAvailable>

                                <Telephone>

                                      <FormattedNumber>(418)555-1000</FormattedNumber>

                                </Telephone>

                                <PostalAddress>

                                      <CountryCode>CA</CountryCode>

                                      <PostalCode>G1R 5C7</PostalCode>

                                      <Region>Quebec</Region>

                                      <Municipality>Quebec City</Municipality>

                                      <DeliveryAddress>

                                            <AddressLine>100, rue Monte</AddressLine>

                                      </DeliveryAddress>

                                </PostalAddress>

                         </ContactInfo>

                         <RemunerationBasis>Salaried</RemunerationBasis>

                         <OvertimeStatus>exempt</OvertimeStatus>

                         <EmploymentLevel>FullTime</EmploymentLevel>

                         <ResourceRelationship>Employee</ResourceRelationship>

                         <EmploymentTerm>Regular</EmploymentTerm>

                         <LaborBargainingUnitStatus>NonMember</LaborBargainingUnitStatus>

                         <ForeignStatus>Domestic</ForeignStatus>

                         <EmployeeGroup validFrom="1987-01-01" idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                                <IdValue name="StatusCode">Y17LT6</IdValue>

                         </EmployeeGroup>

                   </EmployeeInfo>

                   <EmploymentInfo>

                         <IsEmployed>true</IsEmployed>

                         <Employment>

                                <HireInfo typeOfHire="NewHire">

                                      <HireDate>1987-01-01</HireDate>

                                      <!-- Note: no original hire dates or adjusted hire dates need to be sent for a new hire -->

                                </HireInfo>

                         </Employment>

                   </EmploymentInfo>

                   <JobPositionInfo>

                         <JobPositionDetail validFrom="1987-01-01">

                                <PositionId idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                                      <IdValue name="Job Id">20</IdValue>

                                </PositionId>

                                <PositionTitle>Assembly Line Worker</PositionTitle>

                                <JobLevel>

                                      <JobPlan>Assembly Line</JobPlan>

                                      <JobGrade>B17</JobGrade>

                                      <JobStep>1</JobStep>

                                </JobLevel>

                                <JobCategory>Shop Floor</JobCategory>

                                <JobEntryReason>

                                      <StandardValue>Hire</StandardValue>

                                </JobEntryReason>

                         </JobPositionDetail>

                         <ScheduledHours baseInterval="Daily">8</ScheduledHours>

                         <ScheduledHours baseInterval="Weekly">40</ScheduledHours>

                   </JobPositionInfo>

                   <OrganizationInfo>

                         <Organization validFrom="1987-01-01">

                                <OrganizationName>Widget Manufacturing</OrganizationName>

                                <OrganizationId idOwner="Dunn &amp; Bradstreet">

                                      <IdValue name="DUNNS">72241</IdValue>

                                </OrganizationId>

                         </Organization>

                         <OrganizationalUnit validFrom="1987-01-01">

                                <OrganizationalUnitName>Quebec Plant</OrganizationalUnitName>

                                <OrganizationalUnitId idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                                      <IdValue name="Division Id">01</IdValue>

                                </OrganizationalUnitId>

                         </OrganizationalUnit>

                         <WorkLocation allocationPercentage="100">

                                <Id>

                                      <IdValue name="location code">87609</IdValue>

                                </Id>

                         </WorkLocation>

                   </OrganizationInfo>

                   <RemunerationInfo>

                         <RemunerationDetail validFrom="1987-01-01">

                                <PayRate currencyCode="CAD">15</PayRate>

                                <PayRateFrequency>

                                      <StandardValue>Hourly</StandardValue>

                                </PayRateFrequency>

                                <RemunerationType>

                                      <StandardValue>BasePay</StandardValue>

                                </RemunerationType>

                         </RemunerationDetail>

                   </RemunerationInfo>

                   <AffiliationInfo>

                         <LaborBargainingUnitMembership>

                                <OrganizationName>Canadian Shop Floor Workers Union</OrganizationName>

                                <MemberId validFrom="1987-01-01" validTo="1998-06-05">

                                      <IdValue>P71154</IdValue>

                                </MemberId>

                         </LaborBargainingUnitMembership>

                   </AffiliationInfo>

             </Employee>

      </IndicativeData>

</IndicativeBatch>

3.1.2          Example A2 – Personal Address Change

June 06, 1998 – William transferred to US branch of company. William changed the family address to New York.

 

<IndicativeData>

      <Employer>

             <OrganizationName>Widgets Manufacturing</OrganizationName>

             <OrganizationId idOwner="Dunn &amp; Bradstreet">

                   <IdValue name="DUNNS">12345</IdValue>

             </OrganizationId>

             <TaxId validFrom="1975-01-01" validTo="notKnown" idOwner="US IRS">

                   <IdValue name="EIN">67890</IdValue>

             </TaxId>

             <LegalId validFrom="1975-01-01" validTo="notKnown" idOwner="US IRS">

                   <IdValue name="EIN">67890</IdValue>

             </LegalId>

      </Employer>

      <Employee changeType="Update">

             <PersonInfo>

                   <PersonLegalId idOwner="US SSA">

                         <IdValue name="SSN">456-11-1111</IdValue>

                   </PersonLegalId>

                   <PersonId idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                         <IdValue name="Person Unique Id">12440</IdValue>

                   </PersonId>

                   <PersonName>

                         <GivenName>William</GivenName>

                         <FamilyName>Jones</FamilyName>

                   </PersonName>

                   <!-- Contact Info includes personal address change to the US-->

                   <ContactInfo precedence="Primary" validFrom="1998-06-06">

                         <Location>home</Location>

                         <WhenAvailable>evenings, weekends</WhenAvailable>

                         <Telephone>

                                <FormattedNumber>1 212 555 1212</FormattedNumber>

                         </Telephone>

                         <PostalAddress>

                                <CountryCode>US</CountryCode>

                                <PostalCode>11217</PostalCode>

                                <Region>NY</Region>

                                <Municipality>Brooklyn</Municipality>

                                <DeliveryAddress>

                                      <AddressLine>4100 Abiline Avenue</AddressLine>

                                      <Unit>15A</Unit>

                                </DeliveryAddress>

                         </PostalAddress>

                   </ContactInfo>

             </PersonInfo>

             <EmployeeInfo>

                   <EmployeeId idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                         <IdValue name="EE Id">320</IdValue>

                   </EmployeeId>

             </EmployeeInfo>

      </Employee>

</IndicativeData>

3.1.3          Example A3 – Leave of Absence

Start Leave of Absence

March 21, 1999 – William went on FMLA (family leave) but decided to use his 6 weeks of vacation so that his leave would be paid. He intended to return work on May 4. 

 

<IndicativeData>

             <Employer>

                   <OrganizationName>Widget Manufacturing</OrganizationName>

                   <OrganizationId idOwner="Dunn &amp; Bradstreet">

                         <IdValue name="DUNNS">72241</IdValue>

                   </OrganizationId>

             </Employer>

      <Employee changeType="Update">

             <PersonInfo>

                   <PersonLegalId idOwner="US SSA" validFrom="2000-05-12">

                         <IdValue name="SSN">456-11-1111</IdValue>

                   </PersonLegalId>

                   <PersonId idOwner="Widget">

                         <IdValue name="Person Unique Id">12440</IdValue>

                   </PersonId>

                   <PersonName>

                         <GivenName>William</GivenName>

                         <FamilyName>Jones</FamilyName>

                   </PersonName>

             </PersonInfo>

             <EmployeeInfo>

                   <EmployeeId validFrom="1987-01-01" idOwner="Widget Manufacturing">

                         <IdValue name="EE Id">320</IdValue>

                   </EmployeeId>

             </EmployeeInfo>

             <EmploymentInfo>

                   <IsEmployed>true</IsEmployed>

                   <Employment>

                         <IsOnLeave>true</IsOnLeave>

                         <LeaveInfo employeeLeaveStatus="Active" remunerationLeaveStatus="Paid">

                                <LeaveDate>1999-03-21</LeaveDate>

                                <LeaveReason>Family Leave</LeaveReason>

                                <LastDateWorked>1999-03-20</LastDateWorked>

                                <ScheduledReturnToWorkDate>1999-05-04</ScheduledReturnToWorkDate>

                         </LeaveInfo>

                         <IsTerminated>false</IsTerminated>

                   </Employment>

             </EmploymentInfo>

      </Employee>

</IndicativeData>

3.2        Example B – Death of an Employee

The following two examples show the death of active and inactive (retired) employees.

 

Assumptions:  We assume the receiving system already has the two employees on their system and would either use SSN or empl_ID to recognize who the change was being sent for.  We also assume that all other data for these employees is correct on the receiving system and that this document is only transmitting those elements that have changed.  In this case only information directly impacted by the death.

 

Example B1 – Death of an Active Employee

 

Example B2 – Death of a Retiree

 

3.2.1          Example B1 – Death of an Active Employee

This xml file is used to exchange the basic data for the death of an active employee.   In this example, Jim Johnson died while he was still an active employee.  Since the employee was still active we also need to transmit termination data to support downstream systems.  The first indicator of a death in the schema is that the DateofDeath tied to PersonalInfo is populated.  In addition, the termination REASON of 'DEATH' signifies why we are sending the related termination dates.  The termination date in this case is equal to the date of death. The LastDayWorked is 4 days prior to the death date to signifiy that Jim was absent from work four days prior to his death.  In addition, the LastDayPaid is set at 3 and a half weeks after his LastDayWorked to show that Jim had vaction time banked up that would need to be incorporated into benefits or final compensation calculations.

 

<IndicativeBatch>

      <TransactionType>Change</TransactionType>

      <CreateDate>2004-06-15</CreateDate>

      <OriginatorId idOwner="Maypole Electric">

             <IdValue name="System Name">HRMS System Production</IdValue>

      </OriginatorId>

      <OriginatorName>Maypole Electric</OriginatorName>

      <BaselineDate>2004-06-15</BaselineDate>

      <RecipientId>

             <IdValue>0RECEIVE</IdValue>

      </RecipientId>

      <RecipientName>Receiving Company Inc  Benefits System</RecipientName>

      <IndicativeData>

             <Employer>

                   <OrganizationId>

                         <IdValue>0873055</IdValue>

                   </OrganizationId>

             </Employer>

             <Employee>

                   <PersonInfo>

                         <PersonLegalId idOwner="US">

                                <IdValue name="SSN">522-21-1234</IdValue>

                         </PersonLegalId>

                         <PersonName>

                                <GivenName>Jim</GivenName>

                                <FamilyName>Johnson</FamilyName>

                         </PersonName>

                         <DateOfDeath>2004-05-24</DateOfDeath>

                   </PersonInfo>

                   <EmployeeInfo>

                         <EmployeeId>

                                <IdValue name="emp_ID">8878987</IdValue>

                         </EmployeeId>

                   </EmployeeInfo>

                   <EmploymentInfo>

                         <Employment>

                                <TerminationInfo>

                                      <TerminationReason>DEATH</TerminationReason>

                                      <TerminationDate>2004-05-24</TerminationDate>

                                      <LastDateWorked>2004-05-20</LastDateWorked>

                                      <LastDatePaid>2004-06-15</LastDatePaid>

                   </EmploymentInfo>

3.3        Example C – Prehire and Cancel

Many times the intention of hiring an employee needs to be sent to a third party. The person is technically not an employee, but information needs to be sent ahead of time.Typically, this is so that the third party can meet contractual obligations (e.g. allow the employee to do online benefit enrollment on their first day of work.)

 

In this example, Jimmy accepts a position with the company but later changes his mind. The first transaction sends basic information about the job and when Jimmy is expected to start working. The second transaction notifies the company that Jimmy will NOT become an employee.

 

Example C1 – Prehire

 

Example C2 – Cancel Hire

3.3.2          Example C2 – Cancel Hire

Information about the proposed employee (Jimmy) was sent in a previous transaction.

Jimmy has since declined the offer. This exchange is used to communicate that Jimmy has changed his mind and will not become an employee. So the new hire process must be cancelled.    

 

In this case the <ProposedHireInfo> element is used to indicate Jimmy has decided not to accept employment.

 

<IndicativeBatch>

      <TransactionType>Change</TransactionType>

      <CreateDate>2004-09-16</CreateDate>

      <BaselineDate>2004-09-16</BaselineDate>

      <IndicativeData>

             <Employer>

                   <OrganizationId>

                         <IdValue>12345</IdValue>

                   </OrganizationId>

             </Employer>

             <Employee>

                   <PersonInfo>

                         <!-- For now, using a legal id for identification (no employee id yet) -->

                         <PersonLegalId idOwner="US:SSA">

                                <IdValue name="SSN">555-11-1111</IdValue>

                         </PersonLegalId>

                   </PersonInfo>

                   <EmploymentInfo>

                         <IsEmployed>false</IsEmployed>

                         <ProposedHireInfo>

                                <!-- note: attribute 'cancelDate' is optional -->

                                <CancelHire>true</CancelHire>

                         </ProposedHireInfo>

                   </EmploymentInfo>

             </Employee>

      </IndicativeData>

</IndicativeBatch>
